Both people managers and individual contributors
 consistently find these Spotlights relevant and applicable for their workplace goals and relationships, as they include topics like: 
Relevant statistics and data that communicate this community’s makeup, impact, and experiences 
The community’s values, priorities, strengths 
Dispelling any myths or stereotypes about the community 
Challenges or barriers members of this group tend to face in the workplace, and 
Celebrating Jewish culture / the joys of being Jewish 
Strategies & tips for what participants can do to broaden inclusion and belonging for members of this community. What’s the call to action? 
  
Re: anti-semitism: 
Anti-Defamation League free training “
Antisemitism 101 For the Workplace
” 
  
April Powers
 
 led this amazing presentation, called "Antisemitism: Understanding and combatting the world's oldest hate" that I mostly attended (had to drop off) on 10/12. The session as planned many months ago, and it happened to fall right when this is all happening in Israel/Gaza. I took a bunch of screenshots (see below) and we’ll be getting the full materials tomorrow (10/18): 
 
  
 
  
 
  
  
 
  
“hide your star of David” 
  
 
  
  
What does it mean to be Jewish? 
What people perceive: white + religion. But there are many Jewish POC 
  
 
  
‘the people of Israel’ – 12 tribes – ethnicity/culture, not ‘just’ a religion 
  
 
Jewish people in diaspora throughout history 
  
 
  
  
Expulsion, violence throughout history, so largely diasporic people 
 
  
Always mistrusted and attacked. In part diversity of this community is a consequence of forced fleeing. 
  
 
  
What is anti-semitism? 
  
 
  
Attacked for who we are, not how we pray 
Blamed for ills in society 
‘Anti-semitism’ was coined by the Germans – racism/bigotry – racialized being Jewish – as a way to advance hatred. Predates current definitions of racism. 
  
 
  
 
  
  
If you think as Jewish people as white then you might think they’re ‘on top’. 
Every 60 years or so something big (negative) happens to Jewish people – including pogroms in Ukraine. Experience in US is unique – you lack full and equal civil rights as Jew everywhere else in the world. A glass ceiling.  Goes up and down – Jewish people embedded in society in Europe, then the Holocaust happens. 
  
  
Rebecca M. Parrilla 
(she/her) 
Head of Business Development 
LCW
